<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-307-322  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 307 322.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 20 1989 v3 n12 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>USDA cultivates plant data base: genome mapping will helpscientists grow hardier varieties. (United States. Department ofAgriculture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Casatelli, Christine.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corn, soybeans, cotton, rice, wheat and pine trees are among theplants being considered for inclusion in a research program by theDepartment of Agriculture.andP;  The project will establish data basescovering the complete sets of genes in the subject organisms.andP;  Theprogram will allow scientists to understand what traits are causedby what genes, so that scientists will be able to splice togethergenetic material that will cause advantageous traits.andP;  Scientistshope to make cash crops less susceptible to disease and drought,maximizing returns from soil and water.andP;  The Department ofAgriculture hopes to use a supercomputer to assemble the data,which for corn alone will amount to cataloging about 3 billiongenetic base pairs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of AgricultureGeneticsAgricultureData BasesGrowthSupercomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>